('DATA_STRUCTURES', 'Easy', 'Which of the following is true? What is the worst-case time complexity of searching for an element in an unsorted array? (Review)', 'O(n²)', 'O(n)', 'O(log n)', 'O(1)', 'B', 'In the worst case, you may need to check every element in the array (linear search), resulting in O(n) time complexity.', 'arrays,searching'),
('DATA_STRUCTURES', 'Medium', 'For interview purposes: What is the average time complexity of search, insert, and delete operations in a hash table?', 'O(n)', 'O(log n)', 'O(n log n)', 'O(1)', 'D', 'Hash tables provide average O(1) time for search, insert, and delete by using a hash function to compute the index. However, worst case can be O(n) due to collisions.', 'hash-table,time-complexity'),
('DATA_STRUCTURES', 'Hard', 'For interview purposes: What is the time complexity of building a heap from an unsorted array using the bottom-up approach? (Refresher)', 'O(n)', 'O(n log n)', 'O(n²)', 'O(log n)', 'A', 'Building a heap bottom-up (heapify) is O(n), not O(n log n). This is because the majority of nodes are at the lower levels and require fewer swaps. The mathematical proof uses the sum of a geometric series.', 'heap,time-complexity'),
('DATA_STRUCTURES', 'Hard', 'Technical check: What is a Trie data structure primarily used for? (Variant)', 'Graph traversal', 'Matrix operations', 'Efficient string searching and prefix matching', 'Sorting integers', 'C', 'A Trie (prefix tree) stores strings character-by-character in a tree structure. It enables O(m) search, insert, and prefix matching where m is the string length, making it ideal for autocomplete and spell-checkers.', 'trie,strings'),
('DATA_STRUCTURES', 'Medium', 'Technical check: In a singly linked list, what is the time complexity of inserting a node at the beginning? (Concept Check)', 'O(1)', 'O(n²)', 'O(log n)', 'O(n)', 'A', 'Inserting at the beginning of a linked list is O(1) because you only need to update the head pointer and the new node''s next reference.', 'linked-list,insertion'),
('DATA_STRUCTURES', 'Easy', 'In typical scenarios, Which data structure follows the FIFO (First In, First Out) principle?', 'Graph', 'Stack', 'Queue', 'Tree', 'C', 'A Queue follows FIFO — the first element enqueued is the first to be dequeued, just like a real-life queue/line.', 'queue,basics'),
('ALGORITHMS', 'Easy', 'What is the time complexity of Binary Search on a sorted array?', 'O(n)', 'O(log n)', 'O(n log n)', 'O(1)', 'B', 'Binary Search divides the search space in half each iteration, leading to O(log n) time complexity. It requires the array to be sorted.', 'searching,binary-search'),
('ALGORITHMS', 'Easy', 'Which sorting algorithm has the best average-case time complexity?', 'Bubble Sort - O(n²)', 'Selection Sort - O(n²)', 'Merge Sort - O(n log n)', 'Insertion Sort - O(n²)', 'C', 'Merge Sort has O(n log n) average and worst-case time complexity, making it more efficient than O(n²) algorithms for large inputs.', 'sorting,merge-sort'),
('ALGORITHMS', 'Easy', 'What does the term ''stable sort'' mean?', 'The sort never crashes', 'Equal elements maintain their relative order after sorting', 'The sort uses constant extra space', 'The sort runs in O(n log n) time', 'B', 'A stable sort preserves the relative order of records with equal keys. Merge Sort and Insertion Sort are stable; Quick Sort and Heap Sort are not (by default).', 'sorting,stability'),
('ALGORITHMS', 'Medium', 'What is the worst-case time complexity of Quick Sort?', 'O(n log n)', 'O(n²)', 'O(n)', 'O(log n)', 'B', 'Quick Sort''s worst case is O(n²), occurring when the pivot consistently divides the array into subarrays of size 0 and n-1 (e.g., already sorted input with first-element pivot).', 'sorting,quick-sort'),
('ALGORITHMS', 'Medium', 'Which algorithmic paradigm is used in the Fibonacci number problem using memoization?', 'Greedy', 'Divide and Conquer', 'Dynamic Programming', 'Backtracking', 'C', 'Dynamic Programming solves problems by breaking them into overlapping subproblems and caching their solutions (memoization). The Fibonacci sequence is a classic DP example.', 'dynamic-programming,fibonacci'),
('ALGORITHMS', 'Medium', 'In which scenario would you prefer BFS over DFS for graph traversal?', 'Finding the shortest path in an unweighted graph', 'Detecting cycles in a directed graph', 'Topological sorting', 'Finding strongly connected components', 'A', 'BFS explores nodes level by level, guaranteeing the shortest path in unweighted graphs. DFS is typically preferred for cycle detection, topological sorting, and finding connected components.', 'graph,bfs,dfs'),
('ALGORITHMS', 'Medium', 'What is the time complexity of Dijkstra''s algorithm using a binary heap?', 'O(V²)', 'O(V + E)', 'O((V + E) log V)', 'O(V × E)', 'C', 'With a binary heap (priority queue), Dijkstra''s runs in O((V + E) log V). Each vertex is extracted once (V log V) and each edge relaxation may require a decrease-key operation (E log V).', 'graph,dijkstra,shortest-path'),
('ALGORITHMS', 'Hard', 'What is the key principle behind the Greedy algorithm approach?', 'Solve all subproblems and combine their solutions', 'Make the locally optimal choice at each step', 'Try all possible solutions using backtracking', 'Divide the problem into two halves recursively', 'B', 'Greedy algorithms make the locally optimal choice at each step, hoping to find the global optimum. They work for problems with the greedy-choice property and optimal substructure (e.g., Huffman coding, Kruskal''s MST).', 'greedy,paradigm'),
('ALGORITHMS', 'Hard', 'What is the time complexity of the Knapsack problem using dynamic programming (0/1 Knapsack)?', 'O(n log n)', 'O(2^n)', 'O(n × W)', 'O(n²)', 'C', 'The 0/1 Knapsack DP solution uses a 2D table of size n × W (n items, W capacity), giving pseudo-polynomial time O(n × W). It''s called pseudo-polynomial because W is a value, not input size.', 'dynamic-programming,knapsack'),
('ALGORITHMS', 'Hard', 'Which algorithm is used to find the Minimum Spanning Tree of a weighted graph?', 'Dijkstra''s Algorithm', 'Floyd-Warshall Algorithm', 'Kruskal''s Algorithm', 'Bellman-Ford Algorithm', 'C', 'Kruskal''s Algorithm finds the MST by sorting edges by weight and adding them greedily using Union-Find to avoid cycles. Prim''s Algorithm is another MST algorithm. Dijkstra''s finds shortest paths, not MST.', 'graph,mst,kruskal'),
('ALGORITHMS', 'Easy', 'What is the space complexity of Merge Sort?', 'O(1)', 'O(log n)', 'O(n)', 'O(n²)', 'C', 'Merge Sort requires O(n) additional space for the temporary arrays used during merging. This is why it''s not considered an in-place sorting algorithm.', 'sorting,merge-sort,space'),
('ALGORITHMS', 'Medium', 'What technique does recursion use internally in memory?', 'Queue', 'Stack (Call Stack)', 'Hash Table', 'Linked List', 'B', 'Recursion uses the call stack. Each recursive call adds a new frame to the stack with its local variables and return address. This is why deep recursion can cause a StackOverflowError.', 'recursion,call-stack'),
('ALGORITHMS', 'Hard', 'Which problem is an example of NP-Complete?', 'Binary Search', 'Merge Sort', 'Travelling Salesman Problem', 'BFS on a graph', 'C', 'The Travelling Salesman Problem (TSP) is NP-Complete — no known polynomial-time solution exists. Binary Search is O(log n), Merge Sort is O(n log n), and BFS is O(V+E), all polynomial.', 'np-complete,complexity-theory'),
('ALGORITHMS', 'Medium', 'What is the purpose of the ''two-pointer'' technique?', 'To sort an array in-place', 'To efficiently solve problems involving pairs or subarrays in linear time', 'To implement binary search trees', 'To manage memory allocation', 'B', 'The two-pointer technique uses two indices moving through data to solve problems like finding pairs with a given sum, removing duplicates, or finding subarrays — typically reducing O(n²) to O(n).', 'two-pointer,technique'),
('ALGORITHMS', 'Easy', 'What is the best-case time complexity of Bubble Sort?', 'O(n²)', 'O(n log n)', 'O(n)', 'O(1)', 'C', 'With an optimized version (early termination flag), Bubble Sort''s best case is O(n) when the array is already sorted — it makes one pass with no swaps and stops.', 'sorting,bubble-sort'),
('ALGORITHMS', 'Hard', 'What is the key principle behind the Greedy algorithm approach? (Refresher)', 'Make the locally optimal choice at each step', 'Try all possible solutions using backtracking', 'Divide the problem into two halves recursively', 'Solve all subproblems and combine their solutions', 'A', 'Greedy algorithms make the locally optimal choice at each step, hoping to find the global optimum. They work for problems with the greedy-choice property and optimal substructure (e.g., Huffman coding, Kruskal''s MST).', 'greedy,paradigm'),
('ALGORITHMS', 'Medium', 'Technical check: Which algorithmic paradigm is used in the Fibonacci number problem using memoization?', 'Dynamic Programming', 'Backtracking', 'Greedy', 'Divide and Conquer', 'A', 'Dynamic Programming solves problems by breaking them into overlapping subproblems and caching their solutions (memoization). The Fibonacci sequence is a classic DP example.', 'dynamic-programming,fibonacci'),
('ALGORITHMS', 'Hard', 'Quick question: What is the time complexity of the Knapsack problem using dynamic programming (0/1 Knapsack)? (Concept Check)', 'O(2^n)', 'O(n × W)', 'O(n log n)', 'O(n²)', 'B', 'The 0/1 Knapsack DP solution uses a 2D table of size n × W (n items, W capacity), giving pseudo-polynomial time O(n × W). It''s called pseudo-polynomial because W is a value, not input size.', 'dynamic-programming,knapsack'),
('ALGORITHMS', 'Easy', 'Fundamental concept: What does the term ''stable sort'' mean? (Concept Check)', 'The sort uses constant extra space', 'Equal elements maintain their relative order after sorting', 'The sort runs in O(n log n) time', 'The sort never crashes', 'B', 'A stable sort preserves the relative order of records with equal keys. Merge Sort and Insertion Sort are stable; Quick Sort and Heap Sort are not (by default).', 'sorting,stability'),
