('ALGORITHMS', 'Medium', 'Review concept: In which scenario would you prefer BFS over DFS for graph traversal? (Refresher)', 'Detecting cycles in a directed graph', 'Finding the shortest path in an unweighted graph', 'Topological sorting', 'Finding strongly connected components', 'B', 'BFS explores nodes level by level, guaranteeing the shortest path in unweighted graphs. DFS is typically preferred for cycle detection, topological sorting, and finding connected components.', 'graph,bfs,dfs'),
('ALGORITHMS', 'Medium', 'Technical check: What is the worst-case time complexity of Quick Sort? (Refresher)', 'O(n log n)', 'O(n²)', 'O(n)', 'O(log n)', 'B', 'Quick Sort''s worst case is O(n²), occurring when the pivot consistently divides the array into subarrays of size 0 and n-1 (e.g., already sorted input with first-element pivot).', 'sorting,quick-sort'),
('ALGORITHMS', 'Easy', 'Technical check: What is the best-case time complexity of Bubble Sort? (Variant)', 'O(n log n)', 'O(n)', 'O(1)', 'O(n²)', 'B', 'With an optimized version (early termination flag), Bubble Sort''s best case is O(n) when the array is already sorted — it makes one pass with no swaps and stops.', 'sorting,bubble-sort'),
('ALGORITHMS', 'Hard', 'Which of the following is true? What is the time complexity of the Knapsack problem using dynamic programming (0/1 Knapsack)? (Variant)', 'O(n log n)', 'O(n²)', 'O(2^n)', 'O(n × W)', 'D', 'The 0/1 Knapsack DP solution uses a 2D table of size n × W (n items, W capacity), giving pseudo-polynomial time O(n × W). It''s called pseudo-polynomial because W is a value, not input size.', 'dynamic-programming,knapsack'),
('ALGORITHMS', 'Easy', 'Fundamental concept: What is the best-case time complexity of Bubble Sort? (Practice)', 'O(n)', 'O(n²)', 'O(1)', 'O(n log n)', 'A', 'With an optimized version (early termination flag), Bubble Sort''s best case is O(n) when the array is already sorted — it makes one pass with no swaps and stops.', 'sorting,bubble-sort'),
('ALGORITHMS', 'Easy', 'Identify the correct statement: Which sorting algorithm has the best average-case time complexity? (Refresher)', 'Insertion Sort - O(n²)', 'Merge Sort - O(n log n)', 'Bubble Sort - O(n²)', 'Selection Sort - O(n²)', 'B', 'Merge Sort has O(n log n) average and worst-case time complexity, making it more efficient than O(n²) algorithms for large inputs.', 'sorting,merge-sort'),
('ALGORITHMS', 'Easy', 'Quick question: What is the time complexity of Binary Search on a sorted array? (Review)', 'O(log n)', 'O(n)', 'O(1)', 'O(n log n)', 'A', 'Binary Search divides the search space in half each iteration, leading to O(log n) time complexity. It requires the array to be sorted.', 'searching,binary-search'),
('ALGORITHMS', 'Medium', 'Technical check: What technique does recursion use internally in memory? (Concept Check)', 'Hash Table', 'Stack (Call Stack)', 'Queue', 'Linked List', 'B', 'Recursion uses the call stack. Each recursive call adds a new frame to the stack with its local variables and return address. This is why deep recursion can cause a StackOverflowError.', 'recursion,call-stack'),
('ALGORITHMS', 'Hard', 'In typical scenarios, What is the key principle behind the Greedy algorithm approach? (Variant)', 'Make the locally optimal choice at each step', 'Divide the problem into two halves recursively', 'Solve all subproblems and combine their solutions', 'Try all possible solutions using backtracking', 'A', 'Greedy algorithms make the locally optimal choice at each step, hoping to find the global optimum. They work for problems with the greedy-choice property and optimal substructure (e.g., Huffman coding, Kruskal''s MST).', 'greedy,paradigm'),
('ALGORITHMS', 'Hard', 'Which of the following is true? Which problem is an example of NP-Complete?', 'Travelling Salesman Problem', 'BFS on a graph', 'Merge Sort', 'Binary Search', 'A', 'The Travelling Salesman Problem (TSP) is NP-Complete — no known polynomial-time solution exists. Binary Search is O(log n), Merge Sort is O(n log n), and BFS is O(V+E), all polynomial.', 'np-complete,complexity-theory'),
('ALGORITHMS', 'Easy', 'For interview purposes: What is the best-case time complexity of Bubble Sort? (Refresher)', 'O(n)', 'O(1)', 'O(n²)', 'O(n log n)', 'A', 'With an optimized version (early termination flag), Bubble Sort''s best case is O(n) when the array is already sorted — it makes one pass with no swaps and stops.', 'sorting,bubble-sort'),
('ALGORITHMS', 'Hard', 'What is the key principle behind the Greedy algorithm approach? (Q35)', 'Try all possible solutions using backtracking', 'Make the locally optimal choice at each step', 'Solve all subproblems and combine their solutions', 'Divide the problem into two halves recursively', 'B', 'Greedy algorithms make the locally optimal choice at each step, hoping to find the global optimum. They work for problems with the greedy-choice property and optimal substructure (e.g., Huffman coding, Kruskal''s MST).', 'greedy,paradigm'),
('ALGORITHMS', 'Medium', 'Which of the following is true? What is the time complexity of Dijkstra''s algorithm using a binary heap? (Concept Check)', 'O((V + E) log V)', 'O(V²)', 'O(V + E)', 'O(V × E)', 'A', 'With a binary heap (priority queue), Dijkstra''s runs in O((V + E) log V). Each vertex is extracted once (V log V) and each edge relaxation may require a decrease-key operation (E log V).', 'graph,dijkstra,shortest-path'),
('ALGORITHMS', 'Hard', 'For interview purposes: What is the time complexity of the Knapsack problem using dynamic programming (0/1 Knapsack)? (Concept Check)', 'O(n log n)', 'O(n²)', 'O(n × W)', 'O(2^n)', 'C', 'The 0/1 Knapsack DP solution uses a 2D table of size n × W (n items, W capacity), giving pseudo-polynomial time O(n × W). It''s called pseudo-polynomial because W is a value, not input size.', 'dynamic-programming,knapsack'),
('ALGORITHMS', 'Medium', 'Technical check: What technique does recursion use internally in memory? (Review)', 'Stack (Call Stack)', 'Queue', 'Hash Table', 'Linked List', 'A', 'Recursion uses the call stack. Each recursive call adds a new frame to the stack with its local variables and return address. This is why deep recursion can cause a StackOverflowError.', 'recursion,call-stack'),
('ALGORITHMS', 'Easy', 'Identify the correct statement: What is the space complexity of Merge Sort? (Practice)', 'O(n)', 'O(log n)', 'O(1)', 'O(n²)', 'A', 'Merge Sort requires O(n) additional space for the temporary arrays used during merging. This is why it''s not considered an in-place sorting algorithm.', 'sorting,merge-sort,space'),
('ALGORITHMS', 'Medium', 'What is the time complexity of Dijkstra''s algorithm using a binary heap? (Q40)', 'O(V²)', 'O((V + E) log V)', 'O(V + E)', 'O(V × E)', 'B', 'With a binary heap (priority queue), Dijkstra''s runs in O((V + E) log V). Each vertex is extracted once (V log V) and each edge relaxation may require a decrease-key operation (E log V).', 'graph,dijkstra,shortest-path'),
('ALGORITHMS', 'Medium', 'What is the worst-case time complexity of Quick Sort? (Variant)', 'O(n)', 'O(n log n)', 'O(log n)', 'O(n²)', 'D', 'Quick Sort''s worst case is O(n²), occurring when the pivot consistently divides the array into subarrays of size 0 and n-1 (e.g., already sorted input with first-element pivot).', 'sorting,quick-sort'),
('ALGORITHMS', 'Hard', 'What is the key principle behind the Greedy algorithm approach? (Review)', 'Solve all subproblems and combine their solutions', 'Make the locally optimal choice at each step', 'Try all possible solutions using backtracking', 'Divide the problem into two halves recursively', 'B', 'Greedy algorithms make the locally optimal choice at each step, hoping to find the global optimum. They work for problems with the greedy-choice property and optimal substructure (e.g., Huffman coding, Kruskal''s MST).', 'greedy,paradigm'),
('ALGORITHMS', 'Medium', 'Review concept: What is the purpose of the ''two-pointer'' technique? (Concept Check)', 'To sort an array in-place', 'To efficiently solve problems involving pairs or subarrays in linear time', 'To manage memory allocation', 'To implement binary search trees', 'B', 'The two-pointer technique uses two indices moving through data to solve problems like finding pairs with a given sum, removing duplicates, or finding subarrays — typically reducing O(n²) to O(n).', 'two-pointer,technique'),
('ALGORITHMS', 'Hard', 'For interview purposes: Which algorithm is used to find the Minimum Spanning Tree of a weighted graph? (Review)', 'Bellman-Ford Algorithm', 'Floyd-Warshall Algorithm', 'Kruskal''s Algorithm', 'Dijkstra''s Algorithm', 'C', 'Kruskal''s Algorithm finds the MST by sorting edges by weight and adding them greedily using Union-Find to avoid cycles. Prim''s Algorithm is another MST algorithm. Dijkstra''s finds shortest paths, not MST.', 'graph,mst,kruskal'),
('ALGORITHMS', 'Easy', 'Quick question: What does the term ''stable sort'' mean? (Variant)', 'The sort uses constant extra space', 'Equal elements maintain their relative order after sorting', 'The sort runs in O(n log n) time', 'The sort never crashes', 'B', 'A stable sort preserves the relative order of records with equal keys. Merge Sort and Insertion Sort are stable; Quick Sort and Heap Sort are not (by default).', 'sorting,stability'),
('ALGORITHMS', 'Medium', 'For interview purposes: What is the worst-case time complexity of Quick Sort? (Review)', 'O(log n)', 'O(n)', 'O(n²)', 'O(n log n)', 'C', 'Quick Sort''s worst case is O(n²), occurring when the pivot consistently divides the array into subarrays of size 0 and n-1 (e.g., already sorted input with first-element pivot).', 'sorting,quick-sort'),
('ALGORITHMS', 'Easy', 'Technical check: What does the term ''stable sort'' mean?', 'Equal elements maintain their relative order after sorting', 'The sort never crashes', 'The sort runs in O(n log n) time', 'The sort uses constant extra space', 'A', 'A stable sort preserves the relative order of records with equal keys. Merge Sort and Insertion Sort are stable; Quick Sort and Heap Sort are not (by default).', 'sorting,stability'),
('ALGORITHMS', 'Hard', 'Which algorithm is used to find the Minimum Spanning Tree of a weighted graph? (Review)', 'Floyd-Warshall Algorithm', 'Bellman-Ford Algorithm', 'Dijkstra''s Algorithm', 'Kruskal''s Algorithm', 'D', 'Kruskal''s Algorithm finds the MST by sorting edges by weight and adding them greedily using Union-Find to avoid cycles. Prim''s Algorithm is another MST algorithm. Dijkstra''s finds shortest paths, not MST.', 'graph,mst,kruskal'),
('ALGORITHMS', 'Medium', 'For interview purposes: Which algorithmic paradigm is used in the Fibonacci number problem using memoization? (Variant)', 'Dynamic Programming', 'Backtracking', 'Greedy', 'Divide and Conquer', 'A', 'Dynamic Programming solves problems by breaking them into overlapping subproblems and caching their solutions (memoization). The Fibonacci sequence is a classic DP example.', 'dynamic-programming,fibonacci'),
('ALGORITHMS', 'Easy', 'Consider this: What is the time complexity of Binary Search on a sorted array? (Refresher)', 'O(1)', 'O(log n)', 'O(n)', 'O(n log n)', 'B', 'Binary Search divides the search space in half each iteration, leading to O(log n) time complexity. It requires the array to be sorted.', 'searching,binary-search'),
('OPERATING_SYSTEMS', 'Easy', 'What is the main function of an operating system?', 'To compile programs', 'To manage hardware resources and provide services to applications', 'To design user interfaces', 'To connect to the internet', 'B', 'An operating system manages hardware resources (CPU, memory, I/O devices) and provides a platform for applications. It acts as an intermediary between users and computer hardware.', 'basics,os-functions'),
('OPERATING_SYSTEMS', 'Easy', 'What is the difference between a process and a thread?', 'They are the same thing', 'A process is a running program; a thread is a lightweight unit of execution within a process', 'A thread is heavier than a process', 'Processes share memory; threads do not', 'B', 'A process is an independent running program with its own memory space. Threads are lightweight units within a process that share the process''s memory and resources but have their own execution stack.', 'process,thread'),
('OPERATING_SYSTEMS', 'Medium', 'Which of the following is NOT a CPU scheduling algorithm?', 'First Come First Served (FCFS)', 'Round Robin', 'Shortest Job First (SJF)', 'Quick Sort', 'D', 'Quick Sort is a sorting algorithm, not a scheduling algorithm. FCFS, Round Robin, and SJF are all CPU scheduling algorithms used by operating systems to decide which process runs next.', 'scheduling,cpu'),
('OPERATING_SYSTEMS', 'Medium', 'What are the four necessary conditions for a deadlock to occur?', 'Mutual Exclusion, Hold and Wait, No Preemption, Circular Wait', 'Mutex, Semaphore, Monitor, Lock', 'Starvation, Aging, Priority, Scheduling', 'Paging, Segmentation, Swapping, Caching', 'A', 'Deadlock requires all four Coffman conditions simultaneously: (1) Mutual Exclusion, (2) Hold and Wait, (3) No Preemption, and (4) Circular Wait. Breaking any one prevents deadlock.', 'deadlock,conditions'),
('OPERATING_SYSTEMS', 'Medium', 'What is virtual memory?', 'Memory on the cloud', 'Extra RAM chips added to the motherboard', 'A memory management technique that uses disk space to extend physical RAM', 'Cache memory in the CPU', 'C', 'Virtual memory is a technique that gives an application the illusion of having more memory than physically available by using disk space (swap/page file) as an extension of RAM.', 'memory,virtual-memory'),
('OPERATING_SYSTEMS', 'Easy', 'What is a context switch?', 'Switching from one user to another', 'Saving the state of one process and loading the state of another', 'Switching the CPU from user mode to kernel mode', 'Changing the programming language', 'B', 'A context switch is the mechanism of saving the current process state (registers, program counter, etc.) and loading another process''s state so the CPU can execute it. It involves overhead.', 'process,context-switch'),
('OPERATING_SYSTEMS', 'Hard', 'Which page replacement algorithm is known as the optimal algorithm?', 'FIFO', 'LRU (Least Recently Used)', 'Belady''s Optimal Algorithm', 'Clock Algorithm', 'C', 'Belady''s Optimal Algorithm replaces the page that won''t be used for the longest time in the future. It''s theoretically optimal but impractical (requires future knowledge). LRU is a practical approximation.', 'paging,page-replacement'),
('OPERATING_SYSTEMS', 'Medium', 'What is the purpose of a semaphore in operating systems?', 'To allocate memory', 'To synchronize processes and manage access to shared resources', 'To schedule CPU time', 'To handle file operations', 'B', 'Semaphores are synchronization primitives used to control access to shared resources in concurrent systems. A counting semaphore tracks available resources; a binary semaphore acts as a mutex lock.', 'synchronization,semaphore'),
('OPERATING_SYSTEMS', 'Hard', 'What is thrashing in the context of virtual memory?', 'When a program crashes', 'When the system spends more time paging than executing processes', 'When the CPU overheats', 'When disk space runs out', 'B', 'Thrashing occurs when a system is constantly swapping pages between RAM and disk, leaving little CPU time for actual computation. It happens when too many processes compete for limited physical memory.', 'virtual-memory,thrashing'),
('OPERATING_SYSTEMS', 'Easy', 'What is the kernel of an operating system?', 'A type of user application', 'The core component that manages system resources and hardware interaction', 'The graphical user interface', 'The file system', 'B', 'The kernel is the core of the OS that manages CPU, memory, and device drivers. It runs in privileged mode and provides the fundamental services all other parts rely on.', 'kernel,basics'),
('OPERATING_SYSTEMS', 'Medium', 'What is the difference between paging and segmentation?', 'They are the same concept', 'Paging divides memory into fixed-size blocks; segmentation uses variable-size logical units', 'Segmentation is faster than paging', 'Paging is used only in Linux', 'B', 'Paging divides memory into fixed-size pages/frames (e.g., 4KB), eliminating external fragmentation. Segmentation divides memory into logical variable-size segments (code, data, stack), matching the program''s structure.', 'memory,paging,segmentation'),
('OPERATING_SYSTEMS', 'Hard', 'What is the Banker''s Algorithm used for?', 'Memory allocation', 'Deadlock avoidance', 'CPU scheduling', 'File management', 'B', 'The Banker''s Algorithm is a deadlock avoidance algorithm that checks whether granting a resource request would leave the system in a safe state (where all processes can eventually complete).', 'deadlock,bankers-algorithm'),
('OPERATING_SYSTEMS', 'Hard', 'Which of the following is true? What is thrashing in the context of virtual memory?', 'When disk space runs out', 'When a program crashes', 'When the system spends more time paging than executing processes', 'When the CPU overheats', 'C', 'Thrashing occurs when a system is constantly swapping pages between RAM and disk, leaving little CPU time for actual computation. It happens when too many processes compete for limited physical memory.', 'virtual-memory,thrashing'),
('OPERATING_SYSTEMS', 'Hard', 'What is thrashing in the context of virtual memory? (Practice)', 'When the CPU overheats', 'When a program crashes', 'When disk space runs out', 'When the system spends more time paging than executing processes', 'D', 'Thrashing occurs when a system is constantly swapping pages between RAM and disk, leaving little CPU time for actual computation. It happens when too many processes compete for limited physical memory.', 'virtual-memory,thrashing'),
