('OPERATING_SYSTEMS', 'Medium', 'Identify the correct statement: What is the purpose of a semaphore in operating systems? (Concept Check)', 'To synchronize processes and manage access to shared resources', 'To handle file operations', 'To schedule CPU time', 'To allocate memory', 'A', 'Semaphores are synchronization primitives used to control access to shared resources in concurrent systems. A counting semaphore tracks available resources; a binary semaphore acts as a mutex lock.', 'synchronization,semaphore'),
('OPERATING_SYSTEMS', 'Medium', 'Identify the correct statement: What is the purpose of a semaphore in operating systems? (Variant)', 'To synchronize processes and manage access to shared resources', 'To schedule CPU time', 'To handle file operations', 'To allocate memory', 'A', 'Semaphores are synchronization primitives used to control access to shared resources in concurrent systems. A counting semaphore tracks available resources; a binary semaphore acts as a mutex lock.', 'synchronization,semaphore'),
('OPERATING_SYSTEMS', 'Easy', 'Quick question: What is a context switch? (Refresher)', 'Switching from one user to another', 'Changing the programming language', 'Switching the CPU from user mode to kernel mode', 'Saving the state of one process and loading the state of another', 'D', 'A context switch is the mechanism of saving the current process state (registers, program counter, etc.) and loading another process''s state so the CPU can execute it. It involves overhead.', 'process,context-switch'),
('OPERATING_SYSTEMS', 'Hard', 'Consider this: What is thrashing in the context of virtual memory? (Review)', 'When disk space runs out', 'When a program crashes', 'When the CPU overheats', 'When the system spends more time paging than executing processes', 'D', 'Thrashing occurs when a system is constantly swapping pages between RAM and disk, leaving little CPU time for actual computation. It happens when too many processes compete for limited physical memory.', 'virtual-memory,thrashing'),
('OPERATING_SYSTEMS', 'Medium', 'What are the four necessary conditions for a deadlock to occur? (Refresher)', 'Paging, Segmentation, Swapping, Caching', 'Starvation, Aging, Priority, Scheduling', 'Mutex, Semaphore, Monitor, Lock', 'Mutual Exclusion, Hold and Wait, No Preemption, Circular Wait', 'D', 'Deadlock requires all four Coffman conditions simultaneously: (1) Mutual Exclusion, (2) Hold and Wait, (3) No Preemption, and (4) Circular Wait. Breaking any one prevents deadlock.', 'deadlock,conditions'),
('OPERATING_SYSTEMS', 'Medium', 'Review concept: What is the difference between paging and segmentation?', 'Segmentation is faster than paging', 'They are the same concept', 'Paging divides memory into fixed-size blocks; segmentation uses variable-size logical units', 'Paging is used only in Linux', 'C', 'Paging divides memory into fixed-size pages/frames (e.g., 4KB), eliminating external fragmentation. Segmentation divides memory into logical variable-size segments (code, data, stack), matching the program''s structure.', 'memory,paging,segmentation'),
('DBMS', 'Easy', 'What does SQL stand for?', 'Structured Query Language', 'Simple Query Language', 'Standard Question Language', 'System Query Language', 'A', 'SQL stands for Structured Query Language. It is the standard language for managing and querying relational databases.', 'sql,basics'),
('DBMS', 'Easy', 'What is a primary key in a database?', 'A key that can have NULL values', 'A unique identifier for each record in a table', 'A key used to encrypt data', 'A foreign key reference', 'B', 'A primary key uniquely identifies each record in a table. It must be unique and cannot contain NULL values. A table can have only one primary key.', 'keys,primary-key'),
('DBMS', 'Medium', 'What is normalization in databases?', 'Making the database run faster', 'The process of organizing data to reduce redundancy and dependency', 'Creating backup copies', 'Encrypting sensitive data', 'B', 'Normalization organizes a database into tables and columns to reduce data redundancy and improve data integrity. It follows normal forms (1NF, 2NF, 3NF, BCNF).', 'normalization'),
('DBMS', 'Medium', 'What does ACID stand for in database transactions?', 'Atomicity, Consistency, Isolation, Durability', 'Addition, Calculation, Integration, Deletion', 'Automatic, Controlled, Indexed, Distributed', 'Accessible, Concurrent, Isolated, Dynamic', 'A', 'ACID properties ensure reliable transactions: Atomicity (all or nothing), Consistency (valid state), Isolation (concurrent transactions don''t interfere), Durability (committed changes persist).', 'transactions,acid'),
('DBMS', 'Medium', 'What is the difference between INNER JOIN and LEFT JOIN?', 'They produce the same result', 'INNER JOIN returns only matching rows; LEFT JOIN returns all rows from the left table plus matches', 'LEFT JOIN is faster than INNER JOIN', 'INNER JOIN works on multiple tables; LEFT JOIN only works on two', 'B', 'INNER JOIN returns only rows where there is a match in both tables. LEFT JOIN returns all rows from the left table, with NULLs for non-matching right table columns.', 'sql,joins'),
('DBMS', 'Easy', 'Which SQL clause is used to filter rows?', 'ORDER BY', 'GROUP BY', 'WHERE', 'HAVING', 'C', 'WHERE filters rows before grouping. HAVING filters groups after GROUP BY. ORDER BY sorts results. GROUP BY groups rows for aggregate functions.', 'sql,where'),
('DBMS', 'Hard', 'What is the difference between a clustered and non-clustered index?', 'They are the same', 'A clustered index determines the physical order of data; non-clustered creates a separate lookup structure', 'Non-clustered indexes are faster', 'A table can have multiple clustered indexes', 'B', 'A clustered index reorders the actual data rows (only one per table). A non-clustered index creates a separate structure with pointers to data rows (multiple allowed per table).', 'indexing,clustered'),
('DBMS', 'Hard', 'What is a deadlock in database systems?', 'When a query takes too long', 'When two or more transactions hold locks and each waits for the other to release', 'When the database crashes', 'When an index becomes corrupted', 'B', 'A deadlock occurs when two or more transactions form a circular wait for locks. The DBMS detects this and typically aborts (rolls back) one transaction as the ''victim'' to break the cycle.', 'transactions,deadlock'),
('DBMS', 'Medium', 'What is the third normal form (3NF)?', 'A table with no duplicate rows', 'A table in 2NF with no transitive dependencies on the primary key', 'A table with only one column', 'A table that has been encrypted', 'B', '3NF requires: the table is in 2NF, and no non-key attribute is transitively dependent on the primary key. Every non-key attribute must depend directly on the primary key.', 'normalization,3nf'),
('DBMS', 'Easy', 'What is a foreign key?', 'A key from another country''s database', 'A field in one table that references the primary key of another table', 'An encrypted primary key', 'A key that cannot be indexed', 'B', 'A foreign key creates a relationship between two tables by referencing the primary key of another table. It enforces referential integrity — you can''t insert a value that doesn''t exist in the referenced table.', 'keys,foreign-key'),
('DBMS', 'Hard', 'What is the purpose of a database trigger?', 'To manually start a query', 'To automatically execute a set of SQL statements when a specific event occurs on a table', 'To create new tables', 'To backup the database', 'B', 'A trigger is a stored procedure that automatically fires in response to specific events (INSERT, UPDATE, DELETE) on a table. It''s used for auditing, validation, and maintaining derived data.', 'trigger,stored-procedure'),
('DBMS', 'Medium', 'What is the difference between DELETE and TRUNCATE in SQL?', 'They are identical', 'DELETE removes rows one-by-one with logging and can be rolled back; TRUNCATE removes all rows quickly with minimal logging', 'TRUNCATE can have a WHERE clause', 'DELETE is faster than TRUNCATE', 'B', 'DELETE is a DML command that removes rows individually, supports WHERE, and can be rolled back. TRUNCATE is a DDL command that removes all rows quickly, resets identity, and typically cannot be rolled back.', 'sql,delete,truncate'),
('DBMS', 'Easy', 'Identify the correct statement: What is a primary key in a database?', 'A foreign key reference', 'A key that can have NULL values', 'A key used to encrypt data', 'A unique identifier for each record in a table', 'D', 'A primary key uniquely identifies each record in a table. It must be unique and cannot contain NULL values. A table can have only one primary key.', 'keys,primary-key'),
('DBMS', 'Easy', 'For interview purposes: What is a foreign key?', 'A key that cannot be indexed', 'A field in one table that references the primary key of another table', 'An encrypted primary key', 'A key from another country''s database', 'B', 'A foreign key creates a relationship between two tables by referencing the primary key of another table. It enforces referential integrity — you can''t insert a value that doesn''t exist in the referenced table.', 'keys,foreign-key'),
('DBMS', 'Easy', 'Which of the following is true? What is a foreign key? (Review)', 'A key from another country''s database', 'An encrypted primary key', 'A key that cannot be indexed', 'A field in one table that references the primary key of another table', 'D', 'A foreign key creates a relationship between two tables by referencing the primary key of another table. It enforces referential integrity — you can''t insert a value that doesn''t exist in the referenced table.', 'keys,foreign-key'),
