('JAVA', 'Easy', 'Which of the following is NOT a primitive data type in Java?', 'int', 'boolean', 'String', 'char', 'C', 'String is a class (reference type) in Java, not a primitive. The 8 primitive types are: byte, short, int, long, float, double, char, boolean.', 'data-types,primitives'),
('JAVA', 'Easy', 'What is the purpose of the ''final'' keyword in Java?', 'To make a variable modifiable', 'To prevent modification — final variables can''t be reassigned, final methods can''t be overridden, final classes can''t be extended', 'To finalize garbage collection', 'To end a loop', 'B', 'The ''final'' keyword creates constants (variables), prevents method overriding, or prevents class inheritance. A final variable can only be assigned once.', 'keywords,final'),
('JAVA', 'Medium', 'What is the difference between == and .equals() in Java?', 'They are the same for all types', '== compares references (memory addresses); .equals() compares content/values', '== is for strings; .equals() is for numbers', '.equals() is faster than ==', 'B', 'For objects, == checks if two references point to the same memory location. .equals() checks logical equality (content). For primitives, == compares values directly.', 'comparison,equals'),
('JAVA', 'Medium', 'What is the difference between ArrayList and LinkedList in Java?', 'ArrayList uses a doubly linked list internally', 'ArrayList uses a dynamic array (fast random access); LinkedList uses doubly linked nodes (fast insertion/deletion)', 'LinkedList is always faster', 'They have identical performance characteristics', 'B', 'ArrayList provides O(1) random access but O(n) insertion/deletion in the middle. LinkedList provides O(1) insertion/deletion (with pointer) but O(n) random access.', 'collections,arraylist,linkedlist'),
('JAVA', 'Medium', 'What is a Java interface?', 'A class that can be instantiated', 'A contract that defines methods a class must implement', 'A type of variable', 'A design pattern', 'B', 'An interface defines a contract of abstract methods that implementing classes must provide. Since Java 8, interfaces can also have default and static methods. A class can implement multiple interfaces.', 'interface,oop'),
('JAVA', 'Hard', 'What is the Java Memory Model''s distinction between Stack and Heap?', 'Stack stores objects; Heap stores primitives', 'Stack stores local variables and method calls; Heap stores objects and class instances', 'They are the same memory area', 'Heap is faster than Stack', 'B', 'Stack memory stores local variables, method parameters, and call frames (LIFO, per-thread). Heap memory stores object instances and arrays (shared across threads, managed by GC).', 'memory,jvm,stack-heap'),
('JAVA', 'Hard', 'What is the purpose of the ''volatile'' keyword in Java?', 'To make a variable final', 'To ensure that a variable''s value is always read from main memory, ensuring visibility across threads', 'To make a method synchronized', 'To mark a variable for garbage collection', 'B', 'The ''volatile'' keyword ensures that reads and writes to a variable go directly to main memory, preventing thread-local caching. It provides visibility guarantees but not atomicity.', 'concurrency,volatile'),
('JAVA', 'Easy', 'Which exception is thrown when you try to access an array element with an invalid index?', 'NullPointerException', 'ArrayIndexOutOfBoundsException', 'ClassCastException', 'IllegalArgumentException', 'B', 'ArrayIndexOutOfBoundsException is thrown when you access an array with an index that is negative or greater than or equal to the array length.', 'exceptions,arrays'),
('JAVA', 'Medium', 'What is the difference between checked and unchecked exceptions in Java?', 'Checked exceptions occur at runtime; unchecked at compile time', 'Checked exceptions must be caught or declared (compile-time); unchecked exceptions don''t require explicit handling (runtime)', 'Unchecked exceptions are more serious', 'There is no difference', 'B', 'Checked exceptions (IOException, SQLException) must be caught or declared in the method signature. Unchecked exceptions (NullPointerException, ArithmeticException) extend RuntimeException and don''t require explicit handling.', 'exceptions,checked-unchecked'),
('JAVA', 'Hard', 'What is a lambda expression in Java?', 'A new data type', 'A concise way to represent an anonymous function that implements a functional interface', 'A type of loop', 'A design pattern for database access', 'B', 'Lambda expressions (Java 8+) provide a concise syntax for implementing functional interfaces (interfaces with one abstract method). Example: (a, b) -> a + b. They enable functional programming in Java.', 'lambda,functional,java8'),
('JAVA', 'Medium', 'What is the purpose of the ''synchronized'' keyword?', 'To make methods run in parallel', 'To ensure only one thread can access a method or block at a time', 'To speed up execution', 'To handle exceptions', 'B', 'The ''synchronized'' keyword provides mutual exclusion — only one thread can execute a synchronized method or block on the same object at a time, preventing race conditions.', 'concurrency,synchronized'),
('JAVA', 'Easy', 'What is method overloading in Java?', 'Redefining a parent class method in a child class', 'Defining multiple methods with the same name but different parameter lists in the same class', 'Calling a method recursively', 'Making a method static', 'B', 'Method overloading allows multiple methods with the same name but different parameter types, counts, or order. The compiler determines which version to call based on the arguments provided.', 'overloading,oop'),
('JAVA', 'Hard', 'What is the difference between HashMap and ConcurrentHashMap?', 'They are identical', 'HashMap is not thread-safe; ConcurrentHashMap provides thread-safety using fine-grained locking (segment/bucket level)', 'ConcurrentHashMap is slower in all cases', 'HashMap uses more memory', 'B', 'HashMap is not thread-safe. ConcurrentHashMap allows concurrent reads and limited concurrent writes using segment-level locking (Java 7) or CAS operations (Java 8+), providing better performance than Collections.synchronizedMap().', 'collections,concurrency,hashmap'),
('JAVA', 'Medium', 'What is autoboxing in Java?', 'Automatically encrypting data', 'Automatic conversion between primitive types and their wrapper classes', 'A design pattern', 'Automatic memory allocation', 'B', 'Autoboxing is the automatic conversion between primitives and their wrapper classes (e.g., int to Integer). Unboxing is the reverse. Introduced in Java 5 to simplify code with collections.', 'autoboxing,wrapper-classes'),
('JAVA', 'Easy', 'What is the default value of a boolean variable in Java?', 'true', 'false', 'null', '0', 'B', 'The default value of a boolean instance variable in Java is false. Local variables don''t have default values and must be initialized before use.', 'data-types,defaults'),
('JAVA', 'Hard', 'Which of the following is true? What is the difference between HashMap and ConcurrentHashMap? (Practice)', 'HashMap is not thread-safe; ConcurrentHashMap provides thread-safety using fine-grained locking (segment/bucket level)', 'ConcurrentHashMap is slower in all cases', 'HashMap uses more memory', 'They are identical', 'A', 'HashMap is not thread-safe. ConcurrentHashMap allows concurrent reads and limited concurrent writes using segment-level locking (Java 7) or CAS operations (Java 8+), providing better performance than Collections.synchronizedMap().', 'collections,concurrency,hashmap'),
('JAVA', 'Medium', 'Identify the correct statement: What is the purpose of the ''synchronized'' keyword? (Review)', 'To ensure only one thread can access a method or block at a time', 'To speed up execution', 'To handle exceptions', 'To make methods run in parallel', 'A', 'The ''synchronized'' keyword provides mutual exclusion — only one thread can execute a synchronized method or block on the same object at a time, preventing race conditions.', 'concurrency,synchronized'),
('JAVA', 'Medium', 'Review concept: What is the difference between == and .equals() in Java? (Review)', 'They are the same for all types', '.equals() is faster than ==', '== is for strings; .equals() is for numbers', '== compares references (memory addresses); .equals() compares content/values', 'D', 'For objects, == checks if two references point to the same memory location. .equals() checks logical equality (content). For primitives, == compares values directly.', 'comparison,equals'),
('JAVA', 'Medium', 'For interview purposes: What is the difference between == and .equals() in Java? (Practice)', '== is for strings; .equals() is for numbers', 'They are the same for all types', '.equals() is faster than ==', '== compares references (memory addresses); .equals() compares content/values', 'D', 'For objects, == checks if two references point to the same memory location. .equals() checks logical equality (content). For primitives, == compares values directly.', 'comparison,equals'),
('JAVA', 'Medium', 'Review concept: What is autoboxing in Java? (Refresher)', 'Automatic memory allocation', 'Automatically encrypting data', 'Automatic conversion between primitive types and their wrapper classes', 'A design pattern', 'C', 'Autoboxing is the automatic conversion between primitives and their wrapper classes (e.g., int to Integer). Unboxing is the reverse. Introduced in Java 5 to simplify code with collections.', 'autoboxing,wrapper-classes'),
('JAVA', 'Hard', 'Quick question: What is the difference between HashMap and ConcurrentHashMap? (Refresher)', 'HashMap uses more memory', 'HashMap is not thread-safe; ConcurrentHashMap provides thread-safety using fine-grained locking (segment/bucket level)', 'They are identical', 'ConcurrentHashMap is slower in all cases', 'B', 'HashMap is not thread-safe. ConcurrentHashMap allows concurrent reads and limited concurrent writes using segment-level locking (Java 7) or CAS operations (Java 8+), providing better performance than Collections.synchronizedMap().', 'collections,concurrency,hashmap'),
('JAVA', 'Easy', 'Consider this: What is the default value of a boolean variable in Java?', 'false', 'null', '0', 'true', 'A', 'The default value of a boolean instance variable in Java is false. Local variables don''t have default values and must be initialized before use.', 'data-types,defaults'),
('JAVA', 'Hard', 'Which of the following is true? What is the Java Memory Model''s distinction between Stack and Heap? (Practice)', 'They are the same memory area', 'Heap is faster than Stack', 'Stack stores local variables and method calls; Heap stores objects and class instances', 'Stack stores objects; Heap stores primitives', 'C', 'Stack memory stores local variables, method parameters, and call frames (LIFO, per-thread). Heap memory stores object instances and arrays (shared across threads, managed by GC).', 'memory,jvm,stack-heap'),
('JAVA', 'Easy', 'Fundamental concept: Which exception is thrown when you try to access an array element with an invalid index?', 'ClassCastException', 'ArrayIndexOutOfBoundsException', 'IllegalArgumentException', 'NullPointerException', 'B', 'ArrayIndexOutOfBoundsException is thrown when you access an array with an index that is negative or greater than or equal to the array length.', 'exceptions,arrays'),
('JAVA', 'Medium', 'Consider this: What is the difference between == and .equals() in Java?', '.equals() is faster than ==', '== is for strings; .equals() is for numbers', '== compares references (memory addresses); .equals() compares content/values', 'They are the same for all types', 'C', 'For objects, == checks if two references point to the same memory location. .equals() checks logical equality (content). For primitives, == compares values directly.', 'comparison,equals'),
('JAVA', 'Easy', 'Quick question: What is the purpose of the ''final'' keyword in Java?', 'To make a variable modifiable', 'To end a loop', 'To prevent modification — final variables can''t be reassigned, final methods can''t be overridden, final classes can''t be extended', 'To finalize garbage collection', 'C', 'The ''final'' keyword creates constants (variables), prevents method overriding, or prevents class inheritance. A final variable can only be assigned once.', 'keywords,final'),
('JAVA', 'Medium', 'Quick question: What is the purpose of the ''synchronized'' keyword? (Variant)', 'To ensure only one thread can access a method or block at a time', 'To handle exceptions', 'To speed up execution', 'To make methods run in parallel', 'A', 'The ''synchronized'' keyword provides mutual exclusion — only one thread can execute a synchronized method or block on the same object at a time, preventing race conditions.', 'concurrency,synchronized'),
('JAVA', 'Hard', 'Technical check: What is the purpose of the ''volatile'' keyword in Java? (Practice)', 'To ensure that a variable''s value is always read from main memory, ensuring visibility across threads', 'To make a variable final', 'To make a method synchronized', 'To mark a variable for garbage collection', 'A', 'The ''volatile'' keyword ensures that reads and writes to a variable go directly to main memory, preventing thread-local caching. It provides visibility guarantees but not atomicity.', 'concurrency,volatile'),
('JAVA', 'Easy', 'Quick question: Which of the following is NOT a primitive data type in Java? (Refresher)', 'char', 'boolean', 'int', 'String', 'D', 'String is a class (reference type) in Java, not a primitive. The 8 primitive types are: byte, short, int, long, float, double, char, boolean.', 'data-types,primitives'),
('JAVA', 'Medium', 'What is the difference between ArrayList and LinkedList in Java? (Review)', 'ArrayList uses a doubly linked list internally', 'They have identical performance characteristics', 'ArrayList uses a dynamic array (fast random access); LinkedList uses doubly linked nodes (fast insertion/deletion)', 'LinkedList is always faster', 'C', 'ArrayList provides O(1) random access but O(n) insertion/deletion in the middle. LinkedList provides O(1) insertion/deletion (with pointer) but O(n) random access.', 'collections,arraylist,linkedlist'),
