('OOP', 'Easy', 'What are the four main pillars of Object-Oriented Programming?', 'Variables, Functions, Loops, Conditions', 'Encapsulation, Inheritance, Polymorphism, Abstraction', 'Arrays, Linked Lists, Stacks, Queues', 'Create, Read, Update, Delete', 'B', 'The four pillars of OOP are: Encapsulation (bundling data and methods), Inheritance (reusing code from parent classes), Polymorphism (same interface, different implementations), and Abstraction (hiding complexity).', 'pillars,basics'),
('OOP', 'Easy', 'What is encapsulation?', 'Inheriting properties from a parent class', 'Bundling data (fields) and methods that operate on that data within a single class, restricting direct access', 'Using multiple functions', 'Creating multiple objects', 'B', 'Encapsulation bundles data and the methods that manipulate it, and controls access through access modifiers (private, protected, public). This protects the internal state from external manipulation.', 'encapsulation,access-modifiers'),
('OOP', 'Medium', 'What is the difference between method overloading and method overriding?', 'They are the same', 'Overloading: same name, different parameters (compile-time). Overriding: redefining a parent method in child class (runtime).', 'Overriding is compile-time; overloading is runtime', 'Overloading only works with static methods', 'B', 'Overloading (compile-time polymorphism): multiple methods with the same name but different parameter lists. Overriding (runtime polymorphism): a subclass provides its own implementation of a parent class method.', 'polymorphism,overloading,overriding'),
('OOP', 'Medium', 'What is an abstract class?', 'A class that can be instantiated directly', 'A class that cannot be instantiated and may contain abstract methods that subclasses must implement', 'A class with no methods', 'A class that is always static', 'B', 'An abstract class cannot be instantiated directly. It serves as a blueprint that defines abstract methods (without implementation) for subclasses to implement, while also providing common functionality.', 'abstraction,abstract-class'),
('OOP', 'Medium', 'What is the SOLID principle of Single Responsibility?', 'A class should have only one instance', 'A class should have only one reason to change — it should have only one job or responsibility', 'A class should have only one method', 'A class should only use one data type', 'B', 'Single Responsibility Principle (SRP): A class should have only one reason to change, meaning it should encapsulate only one piece of functionality. This promotes high cohesion and easier maintenance.', 'solid,srp,design-principles'),
('OOP', 'Easy', 'What is inheritance in OOP?', 'A class copying another class''s data', 'A mechanism where a class (child) inherits properties and behaviors from another class (parent)', 'Two classes with the same name', 'A type of loop', 'B', 'Inheritance allows a child class to reuse the fields and methods of a parent class, adding its own specializations. It promotes code reuse and establishes an ''is-a'' relationship.', 'inheritance,basics'),
('OOP', 'Hard', 'What is the Dependency Inversion Principle?', 'Low-level modules should depend on high-level modules', 'High-level modules should not depend on low-level modules; both should depend on abstractions', 'Dependencies should be circular', 'All classes should be independent', 'B', 'DIP states that high-level modules shouldn''t depend on low-level modules — both should depend on abstractions (interfaces). This decouples components, making the system more flexible and testable.', 'solid,dip,design-principles'),
('OOP', 'Medium', 'What is composition in OOP, and how does it differ from inheritance?', 'They are the same', 'Composition means a class contains objects of other classes (''has-a''); inheritance means a class extends another (''is-a'')', 'Composition is only for interfaces', 'Inheritance is always preferred', 'B', 'Composition expresses a ''has-a'' relationship (a Car has an Engine). Inheritance expresses ''is-a'' (a Dog is an Animal). Composition is often preferred as it''s more flexible and avoids tight coupling.', 'composition,inheritance,design'),
('OOP', 'Hard', 'What is the Singleton design pattern?', 'A class with only one method', 'A pattern that ensures a class has only one instance and provides a global point of access to it', 'A class that cannot be inherited', 'A pattern for creating multiple objects quickly', 'B', 'Singleton restricts instantiation to a single instance (private constructor, static getInstance() method). Used for shared resources like database connections, loggers, and configuration managers.', 'design-patterns,singleton'),
('OOP', 'Hard', 'What is the Observer design pattern?', 'A pattern where one object watches another''s memory', 'A pattern where an object (subject) maintains a list of dependents (observers) and notifies them of state changes', 'A logging mechanism', 'A pattern for creating objects', 'B', 'Observer defines a one-to-many dependency. When the subject changes state, all registered observers are notified automatically. Used in event handling, MVC architecture, and reactive programming.', 'design-patterns,observer'),
('OOP', 'Easy', 'What is polymorphism?', 'Having multiple constructors', 'The ability of objects of different classes to respond to the same method call in different ways', 'Creating many objects from one class', 'A type of data structure', 'B', 'Polymorphism (''many forms'') allows objects of different types to be treated through a common interface. A method call like animal.speak() can produce ''Bark'' for Dog and ''Meow'' for Cat.', 'polymorphism,basics'),
('OOP', 'Medium', 'What is the Factory design pattern?', 'A pattern for deleting objects', 'A creational pattern that provides an interface for creating objects without specifying exact classes', 'A pattern for sorting objects', 'A pattern for connecting to databases', 'B', 'Factory Method defines an interface for creating objects but lets subclasses decide which class to instantiate. It decouples object creation from usage, following the Open/Closed Principle.', 'design-patterns,factory'),
