('OOP', 'Hard', 'Technical check: What is the Observer design pattern? (Concept Check)', 'A logging mechanism', 'A pattern where an object (subject) maintains a list of dependents (observers) and notifies them of state changes', 'A pattern for creating objects', 'A pattern where one object watches another''s memory', 'B', 'Observer defines a one-to-many dependency. When the subject changes state, all registered observers are notified automatically. Used in event handling, MVC architecture, and reactive programming.', 'design-patterns,observer'),
('OOP', 'Medium', 'Review concept: What is composition in OOP, and how does it differ from inheritance? (Concept Check)', 'They are the same', 'Composition means a class contains objects of other classes (''has-a''); inheritance means a class extends another (''is-a'')', 'Composition is only for interfaces', 'Inheritance is always preferred', 'B', 'Composition expresses a ''has-a'' relationship (a Car has an Engine). Inheritance expresses ''is-a'' (a Dog is an Animal). Composition is often preferred as it''s more flexible and avoids tight coupling.', 'composition,inheritance,design'),
('OOP', 'Medium', 'Fundamental concept: What is composition in OOP, and how does it differ from inheritance? (Review)', 'Inheritance is always preferred', 'Composition means a class contains objects of other classes (''has-a''); inheritance means a class extends another (''is-a'')', 'They are the same', 'Composition is only for interfaces', 'B', 'Composition expresses a ''has-a'' relationship (a Car has an Engine). Inheritance expresses ''is-a'' (a Dog is an Animal). Composition is often preferred as it''s more flexible and avoids tight coupling.', 'composition,inheritance,design'),
('OOP', 'Easy', 'Which of the following is true? What is inheritance in OOP? (Concept Check)', 'A type of loop', 'A mechanism where a class (child) inherits properties and behaviors from another class (parent)', 'Two classes with the same name', 'A class copying another class''s data', 'B', 'Inheritance allows a child class to reuse the fields and methods of a parent class, adding its own specializations. It promotes code reuse and establishes an ''is-a'' relationship.', 'inheritance,basics'),
('OOP', 'Easy', 'What is inheritance in OOP? (Practice)', 'A class copying another class''s data', 'A mechanism where a class (child) inherits properties and behaviors from another class (parent)', 'A type of loop', 'Two classes with the same name', 'B', 'Inheritance allows a child class to reuse the fields and methods of a parent class, adding its own specializations. It promotes code reuse and establishes an ''is-a'' relationship.', 'inheritance,basics'),
('COMPUTER_NETWORKS', 'Easy', 'How many layers does the OSI model have?', '5', '6', '7', '4', 'C', 'The OSI (Open Systems Interconnection) model has 7 layers: Physical, Data Link, Network, Transport, Session, Presentation, and Application.', 'osi-model,layers'),
('COMPUTER_NETWORKS', 'Easy', 'What protocol is used to resolve domain names to IP addresses?', 'FTP', 'HTTP', 'DNS', 'SMTP', 'C', 'DNS (Domain Name System) translates human-readable domain names (like google.com) into IP addresses (like 142.250.190.14) that computers use to identify each other on the network.', 'dns,protocols'),
('COMPUTER_NETWORKS', 'Medium', 'What is the main difference between TCP and UDP?', 'TCP is faster than UDP', 'TCP is connection-oriented and reliable; UDP is connectionless and unreliable but faster', 'UDP guarantees delivery; TCP does not', 'TCP is used for video; UDP is used for web browsing', 'B', 'TCP provides reliable, ordered, error-checked delivery using connections and acknowledgments. UDP is connectionless, faster, but doesn''t guarantee delivery. TCP: web/email. UDP: streaming/gaming/DNS.', 'tcp,udp,transport'),
('COMPUTER_NETWORKS', 'Medium', 'What does HTTP status code 404 mean?', 'Server Error', 'Unauthorized', 'Not Found', 'OK', 'C', 'HTTP 404 means the requested resource was not found on the server. Common codes: 200 (OK), 301 (Moved), 400 (Bad Request), 401 (Unauthorized), 403 (Forbidden), 500 (Server Error).', 'http,status-codes'),
('COMPUTER_NETWORKS', 'Medium', 'What is the purpose of a subnet mask?', 'To encrypt network traffic', 'To divide an IP address into network and host portions, defining the network boundary', 'To speed up internet connections', 'To block malware', 'B', 'A subnet mask defines which part of an IP address is the network portion and which is the host portion. For example, 255.255.255.0 means the first 24 bits identify the network.', 'subnetting,ip-addressing'),
('COMPUTER_NETWORKS', 'Easy', 'Which layer of the OSI model is responsible for routing packets?', 'Data Link Layer', 'Network Layer', 'Transport Layer', 'Application Layer', 'B', 'The Network Layer (Layer 3) handles routing, forwarding, and addressing (IP). Routers operate at this layer. It determines the best path for data to travel from source to destination.', 'osi-model,network-layer,routing'),
('COMPUTER_NETWORKS', 'Hard', 'What is the three-way handshake in TCP?', 'A security protocol', 'The process of establishing a TCP connection: SYN, SYN-ACK, ACK', 'A method for routing packets', 'A data compression technique', 'B', 'TCP three-way handshake: (1) Client sends SYN, (2) Server responds with SYN-ACK, (3) Client sends ACK. This establishes a reliable connection before data transfer begins.', 'tcp,handshake,connection'),
('COMPUTER_NETWORKS', 'Hard', 'What is the difference between a hub, switch, and router?', 'They are all the same device', 'Hub broadcasts to all ports (L1); Switch forwards to specific ports using MAC (L2); Router routes between networks using IP (L3)', 'Hub is the most advanced device', 'Routers only work in LANs', 'B', 'Hub: broadcasts all traffic to all ports (Layer 1). Switch: learns MAC addresses and forwards to specific ports (Layer 2). Router: routes between different networks using IP addresses (Layer 3).', 'devices,hub,switch,router'),
('COMPUTER_NETWORKS', 'Easy', 'What does HTTPS stand for?', 'HyperText Transfer Protocol Standard', 'HyperText Transfer Protocol Secure', 'High Traffic Transfer Protocol Service', 'Host Transfer Protocol System', 'B', 'HTTPS is HTTP with encryption via TLS/SSL. It ensures confidentiality, integrity, and authentication for web communications. The padlock icon in browsers indicates HTTPS.', 'https,security,encryption'),
('COMPUTER_NETWORKS', 'Medium', 'What is ARP (Address Resolution Protocol) used for?', 'Converting domain names to IPs', 'Mapping IP addresses to MAC addresses on a local network', 'Encrypting data', 'Routing packets between networks', 'B', 'ARP resolves IP addresses to MAC (hardware) addresses within a local network. When a device knows the IP but needs the MAC address to send a frame, it broadcasts an ARP request.', 'arp,mac-address,layer2'),
('COMPUTER_NETWORKS', 'Hard', 'What is the difference between IPv4 and IPv6?', 'They are the same protocol', 'IPv4 uses 32-bit addresses (4.3 billion); IPv6 uses 128-bit addresses (virtually unlimited)', 'IPv6 is slower than IPv4', 'IPv4 supports more addresses than IPv6', 'B', 'IPv4: 32-bit addresses (e.g., 192.168.1.1), ~4.3 billion addresses. IPv6: 128-bit addresses (e.g., 2001:db8::1), ~3.4×10^38 addresses. IPv6 also improves routing, security (IPsec built-in), and eliminates NAT.', 'ipv4,ipv6,addressing'),
('COMPUTER_NETWORKS', 'Medium', 'What is NAT (Network Address Translation)?', 'A routing protocol', 'A technique that maps private IP addresses to public IP addresses for internet access', 'A type of firewall', 'A DNS feature', 'B', 'NAT allows multiple devices on a private network to share a single public IP address. The router translates private IPs to the public IP for outgoing traffic and reverses for incoming traffic.', 'nat,ip-addressing,networking'),
('COMPUTER_NETWORKS', 'Medium', 'Technical check: What is the purpose of a subnet mask? (Review)', 'To speed up internet connections', 'To divide an IP address into network and host portions, defining the network boundary', 'To block malware', 'To encrypt network traffic', 'B', 'A subnet mask defines which part of an IP address is the network portion and which is the host portion. For example, 255.255.255.0 means the first 24 bits identify the network.', 'subnetting,ip-addressing'),
('COMPUTER_NETWORKS', 'Medium', 'Which of the following is true? What is the purpose of a subnet mask?', 'To divide an IP address into network and host portions, defining the network boundary', 'To speed up internet connections', 'To encrypt network traffic', 'To block malware', 'A', 'A subnet mask defines which part of an IP address is the network portion and which is the host portion. For example, 255.255.255.0 means the first 24 bits identify the network.', 'subnetting,ip-addressing'),
('COMPUTER_NETWORKS', 'Medium', 'In typical scenarios, What is NAT (Network Address Translation)? (Practice)', 'A type of firewall', 'A routing protocol', 'A DNS feature', 'A technique that maps private IP addresses to public IP addresses for internet access', 'D', 'NAT allows multiple devices on a private network to share a single public IP address. The router translates private IPs to the public IP for outgoing traffic and reverses for incoming traffic.', 'nat,ip-addressing,networking'),
